ğŸ—ï¸ 1. Spatial & Geometrical Reasoning
Testing the "Mental Mapping" capabilities of non-visual models.

Test 1.1: The Origami Coordinate Challenge

"Describe folding a standard 8.5x11 sheet of paper into a crane. You must provide the exact X-Y-Z Cartesian coordinates for every corner (A, B, C, D) after every single fold. If a corner moves, calculate its new position relative to the center (0,0,0). No vague descriptions allowed."

Test 1.2: The Rotating Transparent Cube

"Imagine a 3x3x3 clear glass cube. A red marble is in the center-most sub-cube. Rotate the large cube 90Â° clockwise on the X-axis, 180Â° on the Y-axis, and flip it on the Z-axis. Where is the marble relative to the original 'bottom-left-front' corner? Explain the spatial transformation."

ğŸ” 2. Cryptography & Cipher Synthesis
Testing adherence to non-standard encoding rules.

Test 2.1: The Caesar-Critique Paradox

"Communicate only in a Caesar Cipher with a shift of +7. Your message must be a 3-paragraph critique explaining why Caesar Ciphers are historically weak. If you use a single unencoded English word, you fail the test."

Test 2.2: The Base-64 Recursive Narrative

"Tell a story about a cybernetic dragon. Provide the story one sentence at a time. After every sentence, provide its Base64 encoded string. The NEXT sentence must begin with the last three characters of the previous Base64 string."

ğŸ§® 3. High-Level Mathematical Anomalies
Testing symbolic logic and set theory over simple arithmetic.

Test 3.1: The Non-Base-10 Calculus

"Solve the derivative of f(x) = x^2 + 3x where all numbers are in Base-7. Provide the final answer in Base-7 notation. Show each step of the power rule application using Base-7 subtraction logic."

Test 3.2: Cantorâ€™s Linguistic Diagonalization

